An explicit solution to the weak Schottky problem

Hershel M. Farkas Department of Mathematics, Hebrew University, Jerusalem 91904, Israel farkas@ma.huji.ac.il ,  Samuel Grushevsky Mathematics Department, Stony Brook University, Stony Brook, NY 11794-3651, USA sam@math.stonybrook.edu  and  Riccardo Salvati Manni Dipartimento di Matematica, Piazzale Aldo Moro, 2, I-00185 Roma, Italy salvati@mat.uniroma1.it
Abstract.

We give an explicit weak solution to the Schottky problem, in the spirit of Riemann and Schottky. For any genus g𝑔g, we write down a collection of polynomials in genus g𝑔g theta constants, such that their common zero locus contains the locus of Jacobians of genus g𝑔g curves as an irreducible component. These polynomials arise by applying a specific Schottky-Jung proportionality to an explicit collection of quartic identities for genus (g−1)𝑔1(g-1) theta constants.

Research of the second author is supported in part by National Science Foundation under the grant DMS-18-02116.
Research of the third author is very partially supported by PRIN 2015 Moduli spaces and Lie Theory and progetto di ateneo 2015 Moduli, deformazioni e superfici K3

Here, and throughout the paper, we write 𝟎0\bf 0 and 𝟏1\bf 1 for strings of zeroes or ones of appropriate length.

One can say that the theory we deal with here began with Riemann’s papers [Rie1857] and [Rie1866]. In [Rie1866] in particular it seems clear that Riemann was working towards understanding what we now think of as the Schottky problem, even though the main immediate application was a proof of the Jacobi inversion theorem. The field then blossomed, with a flurry of activity by A. Krazer, W. Wirtinger, M. Noether, F. Schottky, G. Frobenius, H. Baker, and many others — see the many references in [RF74]. In the middle of the 20th century the interest in the Schottky problem seems to have waned, probably due to the fact that the length of the identities increased exponentially, and not much new was discovered on the classical Schottky problem. The interest in the subject was then rekindled in the 1970s in particular by Rauch’s rediscovery of [SJ1909], where what are now called the Schottky-Jung proportionalities were stated without proof. These were proven rigorously by the first author [Far70], and their connection with the Schottky problem was discussed in [FR70]. A period of intense activity followed, including Mumford’s development of the algebraic theory of the theta function, and integrable systems entering the picture.

Various approaches to the Schottky problem were developed by the 1980s, and various geometric solutions to the problem were then obtained (surveyed eg. in [vGe98, Gru12]). Igusa [Igu82a] and Freitag [Fre83] showed that Schottky’s original equation [Sch1888] gives indeed the solution to the Schottky problem in genus 4. Accola [Acc83] gave a collection of equations in theta constants that characterize the Jacobian locus in genus 5, up to additional irreducible components. Arbarello and De Concini [ADC84] showed that there exists a finite set of equations in theta constants and their derivatives that characterize Jacobians (however, making them explicit requires elimination of 3​g3𝑔3g complex numbers from a system of equations). Shiota [Shi86] proved Novikov’s conjecture characterizing Jacobians by their theta function satisfying the KP equation, and various other approaches were developed.

In a spirit closest to the current paper, van Geemen [vGe84] and Donagi [Don87a] showed that the classical Schottky-Jung approach gave a weak solution to the Schottky problem — however, their results do not lead to explicit equations, as we will explain shortly.

More recently, Krichever [Kri10] proved the celebrated Welters’ [Wel84] trisecant conjecture, characterizing Jacobians by their Kummer varieties having trisecant lines. We hope that our explicit solution of the weak Schottky problem, motivated by the viewpoint of [RF74], may lead to a further rejuvenation of interest in this classical subject.

We now state the Schottky problem more precisely, and motivate our main theorem. Denote by ℳgsubscriptℳ𝑔{\mathcal{M}}_{g} the moduli space of curves of genus g𝑔g, denote by 𝒜gsubscript𝒜𝑔{\mathcal{A}}_{g} the moduli space of complex principally polarized abelian varieties (ppav) of dimension g𝑔g, and denote J:ℳg→𝒜g:𝐽→subscriptℳ𝑔subscript𝒜𝑔J:{\mathcal{M}}_{g}\to{\mathcal{A}}_{g} the Torelli morphism. The Schottky problem is to characterize the locus of Jacobians 𝒥gsubscript𝒥𝑔{\mathcal{J}}_{g}, which is defined to be the closure of J​(ℳg)𝐽subscriptℳ𝑔J({\mathcal{M}}_{g}) in 𝒜gsubscript𝒜𝑔{\mathcal{A}}_{g}.

The classical Schottky problem, studied by Riemann and Schottky, is to write down the defining equations for𝒥gsubscript𝒥𝑔{\mathcal{J}}_{g}. More precisely, recall that theta constants with characteristics define an embedding T​h:𝒜g​(4,8)↪ℙ2g−1​(2g+1)−1:𝑇ℎ↪subscript𝒜𝑔48superscriptℙsuperscript2𝑔1superscript2𝑔11Th:{\mathcal{A}}_{g}(4,8)\hookrightarrow{\mathbb{P}}^{2^{g-1}(2^{g}+1)-1} of the level cover of 𝒜gsubscript𝒜𝑔{\mathcal{A}}_{g} (see the next section for details), and the classical Schottky problem is to determine the defining ideal ℐgJsuperscriptsubscriptℐ𝑔𝐽{\mathcal{I}}_{g}^{J} of T​h​(𝒥g​(4,8))⊂T​h​(𝒜g​(4,8))𝑇ℎsubscript𝒥𝑔48𝑇ℎsubscript𝒜𝑔48Th({\mathcal{J}}_{g}(4,8))\subset Th({\mathcal{A}}_{g}(4,8)). The weak Schottky problem is the problem of characterizing the locus of Jacobians up to extra irreducible components. Classically, this means finding an ideal Igsubscript𝐼𝑔I_{g} of polynomials in theta constants, such that the zero locus of Igsubscript𝐼𝑔I_{g} within T​h​(𝒜g​(4,8))𝑇ℎsubscript𝒜𝑔48Th({\mathcal{A}}_{g}(4,8)) contains T​h​(𝒥g​(4,8))𝑇ℎsubscript𝒥𝑔48Th({\mathcal{J}}_{g}(4,8)) as an irreducible component.

The Schottky problem is non-trivial for g≥4𝑔4g\geq 4, and Schottky’s original equation solves the classical Schottky problem in genus 4, as discussed above. Despite many approaches to the Schottky problem having been developed, a solution to the classical Schottky problem and its weak version have remained elusive for any genus g≥5𝑔5g\geq 5.

The Schottky-Jung proportionalities (reviewed in section 3) relate theta constants of a genus g𝑔g Jacobian to the theta constants of its Prym, which is a (g−1)𝑔1(g-1)-dimensional ppav. More precisely, denote by ℛgsubscriptℛ𝑔{\mathcal{R}}_{g} the moduli space of connected unramified double covers of smooth genus g𝑔g curves, thought of as pairs consisting of a curve C∈ℳg𝐶subscriptℳ𝑔C\in{\mathcal{M}}_{g} and a non-zero two-torsion point η𝜂\eta on the Jacobian of C𝐶C. The Prym construction is the map P​r:ℛg→𝒜g−1:𝑃𝑟→subscriptℛ𝑔subscript𝒜𝑔1Pr:{\mathcal{R}}_{g}\to{\mathcal{A}}_{g-1}, and the Schottky-Jung proportionalities relate the theta constants of P​r​(C,η)𝑃𝑟𝐶𝜂Pr(C,\eta) and of C𝐶C.

Let ℐgAsuperscriptsubscriptℐ𝑔𝐴{\mathcal{I}}_{g}^{A} denote the defining ideal of T​h​(𝒜g​(4,8))⊂ℙ2g−1​(2g+1)−1𝑇ℎsubscript𝒜𝑔48superscriptℙsuperscript2𝑔1superscript2𝑔11Th({\mathcal{A}}_{g}(4,8))\subset{\mathbb{P}}^{2^{g-1}(2^{g}+1)-1}. Applying the Schottky-Jung proportionalities to each theta constant appearing in a polynomial P∈ℐg−1A𝑃superscriptsubscriptℐ𝑔1𝐴P\in{\mathcal{I}}_{g-1}^{A} yields an element S​Jη​(P)∈ℐgJ𝑆superscript𝐽𝜂𝑃superscriptsubscriptℐ𝑔𝐽SJ^{\eta}(P)\in{\mathcal{I}}_{g}^{J}, which we will call the corresponding Schottky-Jung identity. The big Schottky locus is the locus within T​h​(𝒜g​(4,8))𝑇ℎsubscript𝒜𝑔48Th({\mathcal{A}}_{g}(4,8)) defined by the equations S​Jη​(P)𝑆superscript𝐽𝜂𝑃SJ^{\eta}(P) for all P∈ℐg−1A𝑃superscriptsubscriptℐ𝑔1𝐴P\in{\mathcal{I}}_{g-1}^{A}, for one fixed η𝜂\eta, while the small Schottky locus is the locus defined by such equations for all possible η𝜂\eta. Van Geemen [vGe84] and Donagi [Don87a] showed that the small and the big Schottky loci, respectively, give weak solutions to the Schottky problem, while in [Don87b] Donagi showed that already in genus 5 the big Schottky locus contains an extra irreducible component, containing the locus of intermediate Jacobians of cubic threefolds. In the unpublished preprint [Sig13] it is shown that in genus 5 the small Schottky locus is in fact equal to the Jacobian locus.

Note, however, that for g≥3𝑔3g\geq 3 the ideal ℐgAsuperscriptsubscriptℐ𝑔𝐴{\mathcal{I}}_{g}^{A} of relations among the theta constants of a general ppav is not known — it is conjectured that it is generated by Riemann’s quartic relations (see [FSM16] for details), but no approaches to proving this are available. Thus for any g≥5𝑔5g\geq 5 the results of van Geemen and Donagi cannot be made explicit, as one cannot write down a set of generators of ℐg−1Asuperscriptsubscriptℐ𝑔1𝐴{\mathcal{I}}_{g-1}^{A}. Our main theorem is thus the first known explicit weak solution to the classical Schottky problem. After our paper appeared on the arXiv, our equations were investigated numerically in genus 5 by Agostini and Chua [AC19].

Our equations Sj​ksubscript𝑆𝑗𝑘S_{jk} arise by applying the Schottky-Jung proportionalities to certain quartic identities in theta constants. The Schottky-Jung proportionalities for ηgsubscript𝜂𝑔\eta_{g} are given explicitly by (7), and since ηgsubscript𝜂𝑔\eta_{g} is invariant under any permutation of columns (and this is one reason for our choice of ηgsubscript𝜂𝑔\eta_{g} rather than η0subscript𝜂0\eta_{0}), we obtain 5: the statement that Sj​k=S​Jηg​(Rj​k)subscript𝑆𝑗𝑘𝑆superscript𝐽subscript𝜂𝑔subscript𝑅𝑗𝑘S_{jk}=SJ^{\eta_{g}}(R_{jk}) for any 3≤j<k≤g3𝑗𝑘𝑔3\leq j<k\leq g. As a corollary, we thus obtain an explicit proof of the main result of Donagi’s paper [Don87a], which implies the main result of van Geemen’s paper [vGe84]:

Corollary 2.

The big Schottky locus gives a weak solution to the Schottky problem, i.e. the common zero locus of S​Jηg​(R)𝑆superscript𝐽subscript𝜂𝑔𝑅SJ^{\eta_{g}}(R), for all R∈ℐg−1A𝑅superscriptsubscriptℐ𝑔1𝐴R\in{\mathcal{I}}_{g-1}^{A}, contains 𝒥gsubscript𝒥𝑔{\mathcal{J}}_{g} as an irreducible component.

(Of course we have in fact proven that it is enough to take Riemann’s quartic relations, as a subset of ℐg−1Asuperscriptsubscriptℐ𝑔1𝐴{\mathcal{I}}_{g-1}^{A}, and among those, to only take those that imply all Rj​ksubscript𝑅𝑗𝑘R_{jk}).

We prove the main theorem by expanding Sj​ksubscript𝑆𝑗𝑘S_{jk} near the locus of diagonal period matrices, and showing that the lowest degree terms of the expansions give a collection of what are called Poincaré relations. These are infinitesimal (i.e. up to terms of higher order) relations satisfied by period matrices of Jacobians that are close to being diagonal. The only such relation in genus 4 was proven by Poincaré [Poi1895]. Poincaré states in [Poi1895, pp. 298–299] that his relation generalizes to arbitrary genus. Our work gives a complete proof of Poincaré relations for arbitrary Riemann surfaces of arbitrary genus. A different proof is given by Fay [Fay73, Ex. 3.4, p. 45]. Rauch in [RF74, p. 228] asks whether in general one can find Schottky(-Jung) identities that imply Poincaré relations, and in particular our work answers this question in the affirmative. By analyzing these lowest order terms of Sj​ksubscript𝑆𝑗𝑘S_{jk}, we then show that in a neighborhood of a generic diagonal period matrix these equations are functionally independent, and thus that the common zero locus of all Sj​ksubscript𝑆𝑗𝑘S_{jk} is (3​g−3)3𝑔3(3g-3)-dimensional, which implies that it contains the Jacobian locus as an irreducible component.

The structure of the text is as follows. In Section 2 we fix the notation and review and extend the results of Fay [Fay79] and the third author [SM85] on the linear span of Riemann’s quartic relations, and show that the identity R34subscript𝑅34R_{34} among theta constants holds. In Section 3 we recall the Schottky-Jung proportionalities, and give the explicit formula (7) for them for the two-torsion point ηgsubscript𝜂𝑔\eta_{g}. In Section 4 we briefly recall the well-known expansion of theta constants near the locus of diagonal period matrices. In Section 5 we recall Poincaré’s notion of “infinitesimal” relations for periods of Riemann surfaces near diagonal matrices, and prove 6, proving the generalization of his relations to arbitrary genus. The proof is by looking at the lowest order terms of the expansions of our Sj​ksubscript𝑆𝑗𝑘S_{jk}. Finally, in Section 6 we combine all of these ingredients to prove that Sj​ksubscript𝑆𝑗𝑘S_{jk} are locally functionally independent near 𝒟gsubscript𝒟𝑔{\mathcal{D}}_{g}, which implies our Main Theorem.

2. Riemann’s quartic relations and their linear combinations

In this section we fix the notation for moduli spaces of curves, abelian varieties, and their covers. We then recall the theta constants, their properties, and relations among them, for the details on all of this we refer to [Igu72] and [RF74].

3. The Schottky-Jung proportionalities

We denote by ℳg​(4,8)subscriptℳ𝑔48{\mathcal{M}}_{g}(4,8) the fiber product of ℳgsubscriptℳ𝑔{\mathcal{M}}_{g} and 𝒜g​(4,8)subscript𝒜𝑔48{\mathcal{A}}_{g}(4,8) over 𝒜gsubscript𝒜𝑔{\mathcal{A}}_{g} under the Torelli map and the forgetful morphism. By abuse of notation, we denote J:ℳg​(4,8)→𝒜g​(4,8):𝐽→subscriptℳ𝑔48subscript𝒜𝑔48J:{\mathcal{M}}_{g}(4,8)\to{\mathcal{A}}_{g}(4,8) also the lift of the Torelli map.

The Schottky-Jung proportionalities relate the theta constants of the Jacobian and of the Prym. They were discovered in [SJ1909], rigorously proven to hold in [Far70, FR70], and recast algebraically by Mumford in [Mum74]. See the surveys  [Don88],[Bea89], for the details of the Schottky-Jung approach, and [Far12] for a survey on Pryms. The Schottky-Jung proportionalities for arbitrary two-torsion point η𝜂\eta, as a relation between modular forms, is described explicitly in

The classical approach to the Schottky problem is as follows. Given any equation P∈ℐg−1A𝑃superscriptsubscriptℐ𝑔1𝐴P\in{\mathcal{I}}_{g-1}^{A}, note that P𝑃P is satisfied by the theta constants of P​(C,η)𝑃𝐶𝜂P(C,\eta) for any (C,η)∈ℛg𝐶𝜂subscriptℛ𝑔(C,\eta)\in{\mathcal{R}}_{g}. Replacing in the polynomial P𝑃P each theta constant of P​r​(C,η)𝑃𝑟𝐶𝜂Pr(C,\eta) by the square root of the product of the two corresponding theta constants of J​(C)𝐽𝐶J(C) given by the Schottky-Jung proportionalities gives a polynomial in the square roots of genus g𝑔g theta constants of J​(C)𝐽𝐶J(C). Since the square roots cannot be chosen globally, to make this a well-defined relation we multiply the product of the results of such substitutions for all possible choices of the values of square roots of the monomials involved — except choosing one square root of one monomial to be given (or otherwise one obtains each factor twice, once with plus and once with minus sign). We denote this product by S​Jη​(P)𝑆superscript𝐽𝜂𝑃SJ^{\eta}(P), and call it the Schottky-Jung identity corresponding to P𝑃P and η𝜂\eta. It is then a polynomial in genus g𝑔g theta constants, of degree equal to the degree of P𝑃P, times 222 raised to the power equal to the number of monomials in P𝑃P minus one, and Schottky-Jung proportionalities imply that S​Jη​(P)∈ℐgJ𝑆superscript𝐽𝜂𝑃superscriptsubscriptℐ𝑔𝐽SJ^{\eta}(P)\in{\mathcal{I}}_{g}^{J}.

5. Poincaré relations

The Poincaré relation in genus 4 was discovered by Poincaré [Poi1895]; it is an infinitesimal relation for period matrices of Jacobians near 𝒟gsubscript𝒟𝑔{\mathcal{D}}_{g} — Poincaré calls it “approximate identity”. Rather than thinking of it as being the lowest order terms of a suitable power series expansion, Poincaré derived it from something he called a “translation surface”. Poincaré then stated that his proof in genus 4 could be easily generalized to higher genus, but gave no details. Garabedian [Gar51] proved the Poincaré relations for some special Riemann surfaces, in arbitrary genus.

Rauch in [Rau71] reproved the original Poincaré relation in genus 4 by expanding a suitable genus 444 Schottky-Jung identity near 𝒟4subscript𝒟4{\mathcal{D}}_{4}, and in [RF74, Appendix 2] asked whether Poincaré relations for any genus could be obtained in a similar way. While Fay [Fay73] proved the Poincaré relation in any genus, we give a direct new proof in the spirit of Rauch, obtaining it by expanding Sj​ksubscript𝑆𝑗𝑘S_{jk} (see 8 for a discussion of why using Riemann’s quartic relations instead of Rj​ksubscript𝑅𝑗𝑘R_{jk} would not work).

The Poincaré relations are the following equations for the off-diagonal elements of the period matrix, for all i<j<k<l𝑖𝑗𝑘𝑙i<j<k<l:

(11) (τi​j​τj​k​τk​l​τl​i)1/2±(τi​k​τk​l​τl​j​τj​i)1/2±(τi​l​τl​j​τj​k​τk​i)1/2=O​(ε3).plus-or-minussuperscriptsubscript𝜏𝑖𝑗subscript𝜏𝑗𝑘subscript𝜏𝑘𝑙subscript𝜏𝑙𝑖12superscriptsubscript𝜏𝑖𝑘subscript𝜏𝑘𝑙subscript𝜏𝑙𝑗subscript𝜏𝑗𝑖12superscriptsubscript𝜏𝑖𝑙subscript𝜏𝑙𝑗subscript𝜏𝑗𝑘subscript𝜏𝑘𝑖12𝑂superscript𝜀3(\tau_{ij}\tau_{jk}\tau_{kl}\tau_{li})^{1/2}\pm(\tau_{ik}\tau_{kl}\tau_{lj}\tau_{ji})^{1/2}\pm(\tau_{il}\tau_{lj}\tau_{jk}\tau_{ki})^{1/2}=O(\varepsilon^{3}).

Note that the Poincaré relations do not depend on the diagonal entries tmsubscript𝑡𝑚t_{m} of the period matrix, which is a priori surprising.

Similar to the case of Schottky-Jung proportionalities, the signs of the square roots in the Poincaré relation may not be chosen globally, and to get a well-defined polynomial equation in the entries of the period matrix, one multiplies the relations (11) for all four possible choices of square roots — this was explained by Igusa [Igu82b, p.167]. As in the derivation of (8), if we denote the three terms in the Poincaré relation by P1,P2,P3subscript𝑃1subscript𝑃2subscript𝑃3\sqrt{P_{1}},\sqrt{P_{2}},\sqrt{P_{3}}, the resulting equation that is polynomial in the entries of the period matrix has the form

(12) P12+P22+P32−2​P1​P2−2​P1​P3−2​P2​P3=O​(ε9).superscriptsubscript𝑃12superscriptsubscript𝑃22superscriptsubscript𝑃322subscript𝑃1subscript𝑃22subscript𝑃1subscript𝑃32subscript𝑃2subscript𝑃3𝑂superscript𝜀9P_{1}^{2}+P_{2}^{2}+P_{3}^{2}-2P_{1}P_{2}-2P_{1}P_{3}-2P_{2}P_{3}=O(\varepsilon^{9}).

We prove Poincaré relations by expanding the factors of Sj​ksubscript𝑆𝑗𝑘S_{jk} near 𝒟gsubscript𝒟𝑔{\mathcal{D}}_{g}.

Theorem 6.

Let C𝐶C be any curve in ℳgsubscriptℳ𝑔{\mathcal{M}}_{g} sufficiently close to a union of g𝑔g elliptic curves. Then after an appropriate choice of A𝐴A and B𝐵B cycles, the period matrix τ𝜏\tau of J​(C)𝐽𝐶J(C) satisfies all Poincaré relations (11).

In genus 4 there is a unique Poincaré relation, for the quadruple (i​j​k​l)=(1234)𝑖𝑗𝑘𝑙1234(ijkl)=(1234), and we first present a streamlined version of Rauch’s computation in [Rau71] deriving it from a Schottky-Jung identity.

Remark 7.

Many other choices of 333-characteristics for the genus 3 Riemann’s quartic relation, instead of (3), and different choices of η𝜂\eta would also yield a Schottky-Jung identity that would work in the above proof. One just needs to make sure that in each resulting R​Ri𝑅subscript𝑅𝑖RR_{i} precisely four theta characteristics have all columns even, and the remaining four characteristics have precisely two columns equal to [11]delimited-[]11\left[\begin{smallmatrix}1\\ 1\end{smallmatrix}\right]. For generalizing to higher genus, to be able to deal with the small Schottky locus rather than the big Schottky, we need to use the same two-torsion point η𝜂\eta for all proportionalities, and thus in our approach the 3rd, 4th,…, g𝑔g’th columns of η𝜂\eta should all be equal, so that permuting them would leave η𝜂\eta invariant. The computationally simplest choice of such a two-torsion point could be [000​…​0110​…​0]delimited-[]000…0110…0\left[\begin{smallmatrix}000\ldots 0\\ 110\ldots 0\end{smallmatrix}\right], but using a computer we checked that for all possible Riemann’s quartic relations in genus 3, applying the Schottky-Jung proportionalities for the two-torsion point [00001100]delimited-[]00001100\left[\begin{smallmatrix}0000\\ 1100\end{smallmatrix}\right] to them cannot give in genus 4 a Schottky-Jung identity where the columns of R​R1,R​R2,R​R3𝑅subscript𝑅1𝑅subscript𝑅2𝑅subscript𝑅3RR_{1},RR_{2},RR_{3} satisfy this necessary combinatorial property. Thus our choice of ηgsubscript𝜂𝑔\eta_{g} is the simplest possible.

We now generalize this computation to arbitrary genus; note that this of course uses the specifics of our choice of quartic identities Rj​ksubscript𝑅𝑗𝑘R_{jk} and of the corresponding Schottky-Jung identities Sj​ksubscript𝑆𝑗𝑘S_{jk}.

Remark 8.

Proposition 9.

For any g≥4𝑔4g\geq 4 the (g−3)​(g−2)/2𝑔3𝑔22(g-3)(g-2)/2 Poincaré relations (11), corresponding to the quadruples of the form (12​j​k)12𝑗𝑘(12jk) for all 3≤j<k≤g3𝑗𝑘𝑔3\leq j<k\leq g, are functionally independent in a neighborhood of a generic τ∈𝒟g𝜏subscript𝒟𝑔\tau\in{\mathcal{D}}_{g}.

In particular, the codimension of the locus in 𝒜gsubscript𝒜𝑔{\mathcal{A}}_{g} determined by these Poincaré relations is locally equal to (g−3)​(g−2)2𝑔3𝑔22\tfrac{(g-3)(g-2)}{2} near such τ𝜏\tau, and the dimension at τ𝜏\tau of the locus of period matrices satisfying these Poincaré relations is equal to 3​g−33𝑔33g-3.

While it is possible to give a direct proof of this statement by showing that locally given t1,…,tgsubscript𝑡1…subscript𝑡𝑔t_{1},\ldots,t_{g}, τ12,τ13,τ23,…,τ1​g,τ2​gsubscript𝜏12subscript𝜏13subscript𝜏23…subscript𝜏1𝑔subscript𝜏2𝑔\tau_{12},\tau_{13},\tau_{23},\ldots,\tau_{1g},\tau_{2g}, all the τa​bsubscript𝜏𝑎𝑏\tau_{ab} can be determined from this set of Poincaré relations, this Proposition follows from the proof of local functional independence of the corresponding Sj​ksubscript𝑆𝑗𝑘S_{jk}, given in the next section.

6. Schottky-Jung and Poincaré: proof of the main theorem

In this section we will prove the main theorem, by showing that the lowest order terms of the expansion of Sj​ksubscript𝑆𝑗𝑘S_{jk} near 𝒟gsubscript𝒟𝑔{\mathcal{D}}_{g} give a collection of functionally independent relations.

Proof of the main theorem.

We first consider the genus 4 case. In this case we only have one identity S34subscript𝑆34S_{34}, and 5 yields S34=S​Jη4​(R34)subscript𝑆34𝑆superscript𝐽subscript𝜂4subscript𝑅34S_{34}=SJ^{\eta_{4}}(R_{34}). The full Taylor series expansion of S34subscript𝑆34S_{34} in the variables τj​ksubscript𝜏𝑗𝑘\tau_{jk}, near the point τ=diag⁡(t1,t2,t3,t4)∈𝒟g𝜏diagsubscript𝑡1subscript𝑡2subscript𝑡3subscript𝑡4subscript𝒟𝑔\tau=\operatorname{diag}(t_{1},t_{2},t_{3},t_{4})\in{\mathcal{D}}_{g}, for all tmsubscript𝑡𝑚t_{m} fixed, is a series such that its lowest degree term has degree 888 in the τj​ksubscript𝜏𝑗𝑘\tau_{jk}. By the computations in the previous section, this lowest degree term is equal to a non-zero multiple of the symmetrization  (12) of the Poincaré relation. Thus the whole series is not identically zero, and consequently its zero locus is of codimension one in T​h​(𝒜g​(4,8))𝑇ℎsubscript𝒜𝑔48Th({\mathcal{A}}_{g}(4,8)) — hence of dimension 9. Since the zero locus of S34subscript𝑆34S_{34} contains the irreducible 9-dimensional locus 𝒥4subscript𝒥4{\mathcal{J}}_{4}, it follows that 𝒥4subscript𝒥4{\mathcal{J}}_{4} must be an irreducible component of this zero locus.

For arbitrary genus g𝑔g, by the proof of 6 we know that the lowest order terms of the expansions of Sj​ksubscript𝑆𝑗𝑘S_{jk} near 𝒟gsubscript𝒟𝑔{\mathcal{D}}_{g} are non-zero multiples of powers of the Poincaré relations for quadruples (12​j​k)12𝑗𝑘(12jk). To prove that Sj​ksubscript𝑆𝑗𝑘S_{jk} are functionally independent near a generic point of 𝒟gsubscript𝒟𝑔{\mathcal{D}}_{g}, we can follow the idea of the argument given in [RF74, pp. 227ff] (which is possible now that we have found Schottky-Jung identities whose expansions give Poincaré relations, and now that we have handled the issue of signs, and ascertained suitable non-vanishing correctly).

Consider the jacobian matrix of derivatives of the Sj​ksubscript𝑆𝑗𝑘S_{jk} with respect to the variables τa​bsubscript𝜏𝑎𝑏\tau_{ab} with 3≤a<b≤g3𝑎𝑏𝑔3\leq a<b\leq g, evaluated very close to a generic point of 𝒟gsubscript𝒟𝑔{\mathcal{D}}_{g} — i.e. for τi​i=tisubscript𝜏𝑖𝑖subscript𝑡𝑖\tau_{ii}=t_{i} generic, for all 1≤i≤g1𝑖𝑔1\leq i\leq g, and for 0<|τa​b|<ε≪10subscript𝜏𝑎𝑏𝜀much-less-than10<|\tau_{ab}|<\varepsilon\ll 1, for any 1≤i<j≤g1𝑖𝑗𝑔1\leq i<j\leq g. To compute ∂S34/∂τa​bsubscript𝑆34subscript𝜏𝑎𝑏\partial S_{34}/\partial\tau_{ab} for 3≤a<b≤g3𝑎𝑏𝑔3\leq a<b\leq g, note that the lowest degree term is always zero except for the case of ∂S34/∂τ34subscript𝑆34subscript𝜏34\partial S_{34}/\partial\tau_{34}. Since each Sj​ksubscript𝑆𝑗𝑘S_{jk} is obtained from S34subscript𝑆34S_{34} by permuting the columns, it follows that to lowest order the only non-zero partial derivative is ∂Sj​k/∂τj​ksubscript𝑆𝑗𝑘subscript𝜏𝑗𝑘\partial S_{jk}/\partial\tau_{jk}. Thus the jacobian matrix is diagonal, plus terms of higher order in the off-diagonal entries τa​bsubscript𝜏𝑎𝑏\tau_{ab} of the period matrix. Since we have assumed that all |τa​b|<εsubscript𝜏𝑎𝑏𝜀|\tau_{ab}|<\varepsilon, the determinant of this jacobian matrix is equal to the jacobian of the lowest order diagonal matrix, plus some O​(ε)𝑂𝜀O(\varepsilon). Since the determinant of the diagonal matrix is non-zero, for sufficiently small ε𝜀\varepsilon it thus follows that the jacobian determinant det(∂Sj​k/∂τa​b)subscript𝑆𝑗𝑘subscript𝜏𝑎𝑏\det(\partial S_{jk}/\partial\tau_{ab}) is non-zero, and thus that the equations Sj​ksubscript𝑆𝑗𝑘S_{jk} are functionally independent. ∎
